Explanation:
The problem requires finding the number of trailing zeroes in the factorial of a given number 'n'. We can solve this problem using a divide-and-conquer approach. We divide the number by 10 repeatedly until it becomes less than 10. In each iteration, we increment the count by the number of trailing zeroes (which is the number of times we divide by 10). The time complexity is O(log(n)) because we divide the number by 10 log(n) times. The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a constant amount of space to store the count. The energy implications are low because the algorithm is efficient and requires minimal resources.

